Velocity distributions were also measured.
Two plastic scintillators, one placed at the
intermediate focal plane of the FRS and another at the
final focal plane.
The nuclear charge was determined using a
multi-sampling ionization chambers-Music.
The liquid-hydrogen thickness of 87.3-mg/cm**2
contained by titanium windows of 20-mum each.
Two additional Ti-foils were used to isolate the vacuum
around the target from the vacuum of the beam pipe
for security reasons so that a total of 36.32-mg/cm**2
of titanium contributes to the empty-target counting.
Measurements were repeated with an identical empty
target in order to subtract the production on the
titanium container from the measured yields of residual
nuclei.
The time structure of the primary beam was a pulse of
6-sec every 12-sec and the intensity was limited to
10E+07 part/spill. This beam intensity was measured
using a secondary-electron emission monitor.

x4freetext: *By authors*.The isotopic production cross section of
each spallation residue was obtained from the
difference between the yield measured with the hydrogen
target and the yield measured with the empty target,
each of them corrected for their dead-time and
normalized to the number of incident iron nuclei. The
cross section is finally obtained after a division by
the number of hydrogen nuclei per surface unit and with
additional corrections due to detection efficiency,
the transmission of the FRS and secondary reactions
estimated for hydrogen events. It was determined that
even at the lowest energy, a correction for possible
change of charge state is not possible.
The isotopic cross sections were obtained for elements
down to z=10 at 300 and 500-MeV/A and z=8 at 750,1000
and 1500-MeV/A with uncertainties around 10% for most
of the fragments. For the lightest ones, the
uncertainty could reach 20% due to the larger applied
transmission correction.
